ected texts in order to reread canonical ones, Kurnick shows that the theatrical ambitions of major novelists had crucial formal and ideological effects on their masterworks. Investigating a key stretch of each of these novelistic careers, he establishes the theatrical genealogy of some of the signal techniques of narrative interiority. In the process he illustrates how the novel is marked by a hunger for palpable collectivity, and argues that the genre's discontents have been a shaping force in its evolution. A groundbreaking rereading of the novel, Empty Houses provides new ways to consider the novelistic imagination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAmerican fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aDramaxTechniquexHistory. 0aEnglish fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aFictionxTechniquexHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aDaniel Deronda.  aExiles.  aFelix Hold.  aGeorge Eliot.  aHenry James.  aJames Baldwin.  aJames Joyce.  aLovel the Widower.  aMiddlemarch.  aRomola.  aThe Awkward Age.  aThe Other House.  aThe Spanish Gypsy.  aThe Wolves in the Lamb.  aUlysses.  aVanity Fair.  aWilliam Makepeace Thackeray.  aantitheatricality.  acollective desire.  acollective spaces.  acollectivity.  adrama.  adramanovels.  adramatic form.  aepiphany.  ainterior monologue.  ainteriority.  aliterary criticism.  anarrative voice.  anovel.  anovelists.  aplays.  apublic space.  atheater.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400840090zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400840090423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400840090.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University P